explanation:
For MISRA dead-code analysis we must know whether each operation in OS_CondVarUnlock actually has an observable effect; the following symbols are required with reasons:

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: The function is invoked and may have side-effects (global state, transactions, diagnostics) beyond returning a value. If it has side-effects, removing the call would change behavior, so its implementation is needed to decide if the call is dead.
- OS_CondVarUnlock_Impl: Called when OS_ObjectIdGetById returns success; its side-effects determine whether the conditional call is meaningful or removable.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Called by OS_CondVarUnlock_Impl (per call graph); needed to see if token-to-index conversion produces side-effects used elsewhere.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit: Callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; may perform initialization or global state changes that matter for behavior.
- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex: Callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; may map IDs and have side-effects or constraints affecting behavior.
- OS_ObjectIdConvertToken: Callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; converts/validates token — may modify token or global state relevant to correctness and side-effects.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: Callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; may perform cleanup or state changes on failure paths that affect observable behavior.
- OS_object_token_t: The token object type is passed by address; its contents/structure determine whether writes/reads are observable and whether operations on it are side-effect free.
- osal_id_t: The id parameter type; understanding its semantics may be required to see whether certain id values cause predictable behavior (e.g., no-ops).
- int32: Return type underlying semantics (signed 32-bit) and any platform-specific behaviour tied to return values.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE: Constant passed into OS_ObjectIdGetById; its meaning can change code paths/side-effects inside that function.
- OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_CONDVAR: Object-type constant passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById; affects lookup and possible side-effects.
- OS_SUCCESS: The success return code compared against return_code; needed to determine the conditional branch semantics and whether the branch is ever taken or removable.

Together these symbols let an analyst inspect implementations and data definitions to determine whether any executed operation in OS_CondVarUnlock is removable without changing program behaviour (i.e., is dead code).
